04396nam a22005655i 9780889207158DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892071587 a10.51644/97808892071582doi  a(DE-B1597)667945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHM484b.M35 2002eb 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a300/.11 aMann, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStructural Idealism :bA Theory of Social and Historical Explanation /cDouglas Mann. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (318 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Charts -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe Nature of Social Consciousness -- tIntention, Meaning, and Structure in Social Explanation -- tA Structural Idealist Interpretation of Theories of Deviance -- tReconstructing the Past -- tThe Search for Depth Meaning as the Essence of Late Modernity -- tThe End of the Search for Depth Meaning as the Essence of Postmodernity -- tA Secret History of the Liquid Body -- tThe Contribution of Structural Idealism to Cultural Critique -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo we determine our actions, or are our actions ruled by the structure of our society? Does our culture create us, or do we create our culture? Within history and social theory there is a fundamental division of opinion between those who explain human action by considering the intentions, reasons and motives of individuals and those who use broader social structures. Structural Idealism presents a theory of social and historical explanation which argues that “idealists” such as Hegel, who champion human agency, and “materialists” such as Marx, who support social structure, have grasped but part of a larger truth. The book contends that we have to explain human actions simultaneously by both the ideas human actors bring to a situation and the way in which previous actions have created social structures that condition those ideas. Through this realization we can see how all forms of knowledge, from the historical roots of modern philosophy to today’s popular culture, both condition and are conditioned by structural ideals. This book challenges our perception of how cultures and ideals are formed, and shows that while structural ideals allow people to co-operate as they work toward goals — their own or those of their community — these images of perfection, so easily accepted as the unalterable structure of our society, can be changed, and are changed, by individuals. Structural Idealism asks us to think beneath the surface of our society, and will be of special interest to philosophers, sociologists, historians and cultural theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulturexPhilosophy. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aIdealism. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207158423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207158/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles